<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEMORRHOID ADVICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON, Neil Solomon is the author of Sick &amp; Tired of Being 
Sick &amp; Tired, Wynwood Press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I would appreciate any advice you can give me as to how I could 
modify my diet to lessen the problem I have with hemorrhoids. I have already 
made it a point to have a high-fiber cereal for breakfast each morning. 
</P>
<P>
Is there anything else? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Whole grain foods, including bran breakfast cereals, should be a part 
of a diet for anyone bothered with hemorrhoids. Other whole grain foods include 
whole grain bread, brown rice and unprocessed oatmeal. 
</P>
<P>
Fruits and vegetables should also be incorporated into your diet, particularly 
apples and oranges, prunes, carrots and green leafy vegetables. In addition, 
try to have six to seven glasses of water, including fruit juices, each day. On 
the other side, limit your consumption of alcohol and stay away from foods that 
are highly seasoned. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to diet, I suggest you participate in a program of exercise on a 
regular basis. This will improve circulation and muscle tone, and help your 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
For Duane, Lansing, Mich.: Polyunsaturated fats are usually found in vegetables 
and vegetables oils. 
</P>
</TEXT>
