<HEADLINE>
<P>
GALA DRAWS ATTENTION TO LUPUS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNINE STEIN, TIMES SOCIETY WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lupus sufferers got some much-needed recognition Tuesday night as the Lupus 
Foundation of America honored Richard and Jeramie Dreyfuss with the first-ever 
Summa award at the Beverly Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
The black-tie gala honored the two for their work in raising awareness of the 
disease and campaigning for research funding. Jeramie, who suffers from lupus, 
husband Richard and daughter Emily, 6, were the focal point of a reception 
preceding the dinner. Nancy Horn, president of the Lupus Foundation of America 
and gala co-chairwoman, and gala chairwoman Glenda Kay Amon were on hand, as 
were Paul Michael and Elizabeth Glaser, Michele Lee and Fred Rappaport, Theresa 
Russell, Richard Donner and Lauren Shuler-Donner, John Lithgow and Alan Ladd 
Jr. Amy Irving, who planned to appear, sent regrets; the actress had had a baby 
just days before. Among the hundreds of other guests were several doctors 
involved in lupus treatment and research, and many lupus patients. 
</P>
<P>
Lupus, an auto-immune disease that has varying symptoms and can be 
life-threatening, affects mostly women and can take years to diagnose. While it 
affects hundreds of thousands of people, there is little public knowledge of 
the disease -- something the Dreyfusses have tried to change. 
</P>
<P>
In accepting the award, Richard Dreyfuss made an impassioned plea for social 
responsibility and heaped praise upon his wife, saying: "I am a busy guy, but 
I'm not as busy as Jeramie. I am a pretty good and decent guy, but not as good 
and decent as Jeramie. But I am a better whiner. I don't live in pain as easily 
as she does. I think we need more Jeramie Dreyfusses both in and out of 
government." 
</P>
<P>
As she wiped away tears, Jeramie added, "I've heard such incredible stories 
tonight, it reminds me why I'm here. My goal is to spread the word about this 
silent killer." 
</P>
<P>
Little Richard got the audience literally on its feet as he played a rousing 
set, culminating with duet with Elton John. The event, underwritten by two 
anonymous donors, raised more than $500,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Jeramie, left, Emily and Richard Dreyfuss at Lupus Foundation dinner. 
ROBERT GABRIEL / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
